(24, '‘Page one of the authoritarian playbook’: how Trump and allies are exploiting Kirk’s killing', 'page-one-of-the-authoritarian-playbook-how-trump-and-allies-are-exploiting-kirks-killing', 'The president and his Maga allies have used the rightwing influencer’s killing to justify attacks on critics, experts say', '&lt;p&gt;Donald Trump and Maga allies have capitalized on the killing of rightwing influencer Charlie Kirk to expand attacks on liberal groups, donors, Democrats, and others by tarring many critics as the &ldquo;enemy within&rdquo; and &ldquo;radical left&rdquo; in a move that legal scholars and historians call authoritarian and anti-democratic.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Kirk&rsquo;s killing by a lone gunman spurred Trump and top allies to quickly launch conspiratorial charges against a bevy of political foes and an investigation of billionaire liberal donor George Soros. They also threatened legal action against TV network ABC after their late-night star Jimmy Kimmel&rsquo;s suspension over clumsy comments about Kirk ended.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;While Kirk&rsquo;s murder was a big personal blow to Trump and allies, a month on from the shocking event it seems to have provided cover for a sprawling retribution drive by the president and Maga world that endangers civil liberties against an array of critics in the media, universities, non-profits and other parts of American civil society, say scholars.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At the memorial for the slain conservative leader right after Kirk&rsquo;s widow movingly said she would &ldquo;forgive&rdquo; his killer, Trump angrily declared: &ldquo;I hate my opponents and I don&rsquo;t wish the best for them,&rdquo; words that scholars viewed as unpresidential with the potential to fuel more violence.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Similarly, even before the suspect in Kirk&rsquo;s murder was arrested, Trump posited that &ldquo;radical left&rdquo; language contributed to his death. He also pledged to go after those people responsible for the violence plus &ldquo;organizations that fund it and support it&hellip; We have radical-left lunatics out there, and we just have to beat the hell out of them.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Further, Trump&rsquo;s escalating offensive against foes was palpable in his talk to hundreds of top military officials last month when he warned darkly about the need to counter &ldquo;the enemy within&rdquo; and suggested the military could be useful in his drive against crime in mostly Democratic cities which could serve as a military &ldquo;training ground&rdquo; too.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On a related front on 8 October, as hundreds of national guard troops were poised to enter Chicago over the objections of the city&rsquo;s mayor and the Illinois governor, both Democrats who had criticized Trump&rsquo;s militarized immigration crackdown, Trump called for jailing them even though neither one had been charged with crimes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Historians and legal experts warn that Trump and the Maga world have exploited Kirk&rsquo;s killing to justify unleashing far-reaching attacks on multiple critics.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Trump and his allies are using &ldquo;page one of the authoritarian playbook&rdquo; in their accelerating attacks on political foes&rdquo;, said Harvard government professor Steven Levitsky, who co-authored the book How Democracies Die.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;You use political violence as a pretext to go after your political enemies. Some of them have been chomping at the bit to do this. They&rsquo;re going after mainstream opponents and other critics. They&rsquo;re defining unacceptable behavior as broadly as possible.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Levitsky stressed that Trump&rsquo;s attacks on Soros and some other major funders of Democrats and liberal groups are part of a broad assault on civil society. &ldquo;The goal is to tilt the playing field by going after anybody in civil society who could challenge them,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;One way to weaken them is to go after the funders using a false pretense by linking them to violence or illegal behavior.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Pointedly, Trump in interviews days after Kirk&rsquo;s killing charged in conspiratorial and evidence-free language that the 95-year-old Soros &ldquo;should be put in jail&rdquo; and was a &ldquo;bad&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;guy&rdquo;. He told Fox &amp;amp; Friends that &ldquo;we&rsquo;re going to look into Soros&rdquo; for possible violations of the racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations (Rico) law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The justice department (DoJ) has opened investigations into Soros&rsquo; Open Society Foundations, which over decades have poured many millions of dollars into civil rights, human rights and democracy programs, according to the New York Times.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Soros Foundations have pushed back hard saying the accusations are &ldquo;politically motivated attacks on civil society&rdquo; designed to silence dissenting speech and stressed all its activities are &ldquo;peaceful and lawful&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Legal experts say Trump&rsquo;s hyped up drive to have Soros prosecuted on Rico charges is antithetical to the rule of law and part of Trump&rsquo;s broader drive to weaponize DoJ against old enemies such as ex-FBI director James Comey who angered Trump for investigating Russian moves to help Trump win the 2016 election.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Last month a Trump picked novice prosecutor filed a two count indictment of Comey for lying to Congress and obstruction of Congress, after Trump forced out a veteran prosecutor who didn&rsquo;t pursue the charges reportedly because of the weakness of the evidence. Comey on 8 October pleaded not guilty.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The same Trump picked prosecutor in Virginia, despite the objections of veteran prosecutors who had been ousted, on 9 October brought charges of bank fraud and false statements against the New York attorney general, Letitia James, who Trump has long reviled for winning a civil case against him and others for improperly inflating his real estate assets. James called the charges against her &ldquo;baseless&rdquo;, and part of Trump&rsquo;s &ldquo;weaponization&rdquo; of the US justice system.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;Trump&rsquo;s invocation of Rico to investigate Soros is frivolously wrong-headed,&rdquo; said ex-federal prosecutor Paul Rosenzweig. &ldquo;It is yet another example of his weaponization of the law to target his enemies.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The threat of more attacks on non-profits was underscored when Democracy Defenders Fund announced on 1 October that more than 3,700 groups signed a letter sharply criticizing the administration for launching a campaign to &ldquo;intimidate and silence charitable groups through executive action&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Besides Trump&rsquo;s retribution moves, Trump&rsquo;s radical deputy chief of staff, Stephen Miller, has branded the Democratic party &ldquo;a domestic extremist organization&rdquo; and blamed &ldquo;terrorist networks&rdquo; for Kirk&rsquo;s murder,&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;vowing the administration would be going after a &ldquo;vast domestic terror network&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;To realize this goal, Trump signed an executive memo two weeks after Kirk died dubbed &ldquo;Countering Domestic Terrorism and Organized Political Violence&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Citing Kirk&rsquo;s killing, the memo laid the groundwork for a coordinated effort by among others the attorney general, the treasury secretary, the IRS commissioner. The memo called for a &ldquo;national strategy to investigate, prosecute and disrupt entities and individuals engaged in acts of political violence and intimidation designed to suppress lawful political activity or obstruct the rule of law&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As part of that effort, Trump designated the leftist Antifa movement a &ldquo;domestic terrorist organization&rdquo;, although under US law no such designation exists.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Specifically, Trump instructed his administration to &ldquo;utilize all applicable authorities to investigate, disrupt and dismantle any and all illegal operations &ndash; especially those involving terrorist actions &ndash; conducted by antifa.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Similarly, the Texas attorney general, Ken Paxton, a leading Trump ally, instructed his office to launch sweeping investigations into &ldquo;radical leftist organizations engaged in or providing support to those performing political violence&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Despite the Trump administration&rsquo;s focus on linking the &ldquo;radical left&rdquo; to political violence, a study in 2024 that used to be on DoJ&rsquo;s website stated that &ldquo;the number of far-right attacks continues to outpace all other types of terrorism and domestic violent extremism.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A recent report from the Center for Strategic and International Studies found that leftwing violence in the first half of 2025 had hit a 30-year high, but it noted that overall since 2016 rightwing violence has been much higher:&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;the study cited 41 attacks by leftwing extremists compared to 152 from the far right in these years.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Legal scholars warn that Trump administration actions against a range of liberal political targets and critics since Kirk&rsquo;s death reflect growing authoritarian tendencies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;Hallmarks of authoritarian regimes include that they seek to undermine independent media outlets and NGOs, dissolve legal boundaries between the state and civil society, vilify critics and marginalized groups, personalize politics, and make dissent more costly,&rdquo; Columbia law professor David Pozen told the Guardian. &ldquo; All of these authoritarian tendencies have been on display in the Trump administration&rsquo;s response to the horrific murder of Charlie Kirk.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Historians too fear that Trump is using Kirk&rsquo;s death to invoke conspiracies for political gains and revenge.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;Since Charlie Kirk&rsquo;s murder, President Trump has amplified and extended his penchant for leveling conspiracy charges,&rdquo; said Russell Muirhead who chairs Dartmouth&rsquo;s department of government.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;The target is &ldquo;domestic terrorist organizations&rdquo;, which seems to include such peaceful pro-democratic anti-communist entities as George Soros&rsquo;s Open Society Foundations. The effect is to describe the entirety of &ldquo;the left&rdquo; as a conspiracy, bent on destroying the country &ndash; including the Democratic party.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Muirhead added: &ldquo;The risk here is clear: conspiracy charges convert peaceful political opponents into enemies. Once that is accomplished, they no longer need to be respected or tolerated. They can be folded into shadowy &lsquo;domestic terrorism networks&rsquo; and imprisoned &ndash; or worse.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Muirhead&rsquo;s concerns were underscored in Trump&rsquo;s 30 September speech warning of the &ldquo;enemy within&rdquo; to an audience of hundreds of top military leaders where he declared flatly that &ldquo;America is under invasion from within,&rdquo; claiming that &ldquo;Democrats run most of the cities that are in bad shape.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Trump called these cities &ldquo;very unsafe places and we&rsquo;re going to straighten them out one by one,&rdquo; a task that would be a &ldquo;major part&rdquo; of what some military leaders will be doing. Trump also bluntly suggested that the military &ldquo;should use some of these dangerous cities as training grounds&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Trump&rsquo;s radical suggestions to the military crowd seemed to ignore the almost 150-year-old Posse Comitatus Act that curbs using federal troops in law enforcement matters on US soil with some loopholes and exceptions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Legal experts too have raised loud alarms at Trump&rsquo;s radical military schemes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;A president with dictatorial ambitions declaring that people in Democratic led cities are the &lsquo;enemy within&rsquo; who have to be controlled by the use of the military is contrary to the very principles upon which this country was founded,&rdquo; said Larry Noble, a former general counsel at the Federal Election Commission who now teaches law at American University.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;One cannot help but wonder whether he will continue to expand the Democratic cities in which he will use the military and whether that military presence will continue through the 2026 midterm election, in an effort to try to undermine free and fair elections.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pozen concurred that &ldquo;President Trump&rsquo;s latest comment to military leadership about the enemy &lsquo;from within&rsquo; is yet another familiar authoritarian trope &ndash; an especially scary one&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;More broadly, legal scholars say Trump&rsquo;s far flung attacks on the radical left endangers the&rdquo; laws and traditions&rdquo; that underpin democracy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;Trump deploys outrageous rhetoric to try to legitimate his unconstitutional overreach,&rdquo; said Peter Shane, who teaches constitutional law at New York University. &ldquo;Whether it&rsquo;s the baseless withholding of funds from private institutions that fail to bend the knee or fantasizing about the use of cities with Democratic mayors to train the military, Trump is running roughshod over the laws and traditions that have long sustained a robust American democracy.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;', 'Peter Stone in Washington', 'articles/68ea5cf801283.jpg', 'published', 'Guardian', 1, 27, '2025-10-11 09:09:09', '2025-10-11 10:34:48'),
(25, '‘It’s a question of humanity’: how a small Spanish town made headlines over its immigration stance', 'its-a-question-of-humanity-how-a-small-spanish-town-made-headlines-over-its-immigration-stance', 'Mayor explains why Villamalea unanimously backed call to regularise undocumented migrants – across party lines', '&lt;p&gt;Flanked by farmland and nestled among the deep valleys of central Spain, few in Villamalea, a town of 4,200 people, expected to find their tranquil home splashed across Spanish media this summer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve never been contacted by so many media outlets in my life,&rdquo; said Jos&eacute; N&uacute;&ntilde;ez P&eacute;rez, the conservative mayor of Villamalea. With a laugh, he added: &ldquo;It made me question, just what have we done here?&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Everyone wanted to speak to him about the same thing; a town council motion, approved unanimously and across party lines, calling on the central government to push forward &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.infomigrants.net/en/post/63767/spanish-bishops-call-for-regularization-of-half-million-migrants&quot;&gt;with a stalled proposal&lt;/a&gt; to regularise undocumented migrants in Spain.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;To us, it was the most natural thing in the world,&rdquo; explained N&uacute;&ntilde;ez P&eacute;rez, as he paused to greet residents in the town&rsquo;s central plaza. In recent decades, migrants from across the globe had been atrracted to Villamalea for the many jobs on offer. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The steady supply of labour had helped turn the town into an agricultural heavyweight &ndash; about 70% of the mushrooms sold in Spain come from here &ndash; while also transforming Villamalea into a rich tapestry of residents whose roots trace back to 32 countries.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;For the 11 town councillors who backed the motion to grant papers to undocumented migrants &ndash; from N&uacute;&ntilde;ez P&eacute;rez&rsquo;s People&rsquo;s party to the Socialists and the United Left &ndash; this reality took precedence over party lines.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;We didn&rsquo;t even debate it, we were all onboard right away,&rdquo; said N&uacute;&ntilde;ez P&eacute;rez. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s a lot of work to be done here. And there could be even more &ndash; the problem for these companies is that they can&rsquo;t find enough people to work.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With the town&rsquo;s companies weighing up whether to bring in temporary foreign workers, it only made sense to allow those who were already here a fair chance at a foothold. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not just economics, it&rsquo;s a question of humanity,&rdquo; said the mayor.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In late August, the president of the European Central Bank, Christine Lagarde, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/foreign-workers-have-boosted-euro-zone-economy-ecbs-lagarde-says-2025-08-23/&quot;&gt;said gross domestic output&lt;/a&gt; in Germany would have been about 6% lower in 2019 if it hadn&rsquo;t been for foreign workers. The picture was similar across the eurozone, she said. &ldquo;Although they represented only around 9% of the total labour force in 2022, foreign workers have accounted for half of its growth over the past three years.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;In Spain, where the Socialist prime minister &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/sep/03/you-need-solidarity-and-consistency-pedro-sanchez-on-the-eu-trump-and-fighting-the-far-right&quot;&gt;has insisted&lt;/a&gt; that migration is an opportunity, a surge in arrivals has helped to &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/18/how-spains-radically-different-approach-to-migration-helped-its-economy-soar&quot;&gt;make the country a bright spot&lt;/a&gt; among Europe&rsquo;s plodding economies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Of late, even some of the most ardent critics of immigration have conceded its necessity; in June Italy&rsquo;s Giorgia Meloni, the far-right leader who &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/17/italian-pm-warns-migration-an-issue-for-all-of-europe-on-lampedusa-visit&quot;&gt;has long called &lt;/a&gt;irregular migrants a threat to Europe&rsquo;s future, said her government &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.reuters.com/world/italy-issue-half-million-non-eu-work-visas-over-next-three-years-2025-06-30/&quot;&gt;would issue&lt;/a&gt; nearly 500,000 new work visas for non-EU nationals in the coming years, in addition to the 450,000 handed out since she took power.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;While regularisation programmes &lt;a href=&quot;https://picum.org/blog/regularisation-and-access-to-a-secure-residence-status/&quot;&gt;have long been used&lt;/a&gt; across the EU, with 43 put in place by more than a dozen countries between 1996 and 2008, in Villamalea the push to grant papers was also rooted in the town&rsquo;s history.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;During much of the 20th century, the town&rsquo;s residents were forced to fan out across Europe in search of work, said Venancio Cuenca Lop&eacute;z, the head of a local retiree association. &ldquo;Some of them had papers, but some had no papers, no job offers, nothing,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;We can&rsquo;t say: &lsquo;Well we did it, but now we&rsquo;re against it.&rsquo; We&rsquo;re all human beings, we need to have some empathy.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He pushed back against claims that regularisation would push down wages. &ldquo;There are companies that take advantage of undocumented workers, forcing them to work in poor conditions and paying them little. Then Spaniards can&rsquo;t work because they&rsquo;re competing with people who are getting paid peanuts,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;So we regularise them, everyone has the same conditions.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Guardian spoke to 10 or so residents, all of whom expressed support for the motion. From the pensioners who make up about a quarter of the town&rsquo;s population to the around 20% who were born abroad &ndash; the majority from Morocco or Romania &ndash; residents shrugged off the far-right&rsquo;s efforts to disparage diversity. &ldquo;Here everyone has their life and their world, but when we get to together we all get along,&rdquo; said Mar&iacute;a Anguix Garc&iacute;a.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At Villamalea&rsquo;s town hall, officials are swift to cite the efforts many have made to foster integration, keenly aware that they&rsquo;re &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2024/nov/26/far-right-weaponising-ai-generated-content-europe&quot;&gt;doing so against a backdrop&lt;/a&gt; of swirling disinformation about migration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;There was a day when people who practise Islam went to the church and got to know the prayer space and then they did the reverse; the Catholics went to the mosque and experienced it,&rdquo; said the mayor &ldquo;And around two months later, the five religions we have in Villamalea came together to pray in the church.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When the flood of media requests poured in earlier this year, most wanted to know how N&uacute;&ntilde;ez P&eacute;rez reconciled his stance with others in the conservative People&rsquo;s party, particularly as the leader, Alberto N&uacute;&ntilde;ez Feij&oacute;o, was &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.eldiario.es/politica/feijoo-vox-instalan-espiritu-torre-pacheco-siguen-buscando-votos-vinculando-inseguridad-e-inmigracion_1_12508625.html&quot;&gt;increasingly linking&lt;/a&gt; immigration to insecurity.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Across the country, PP politicians have entered into governments &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jul/21/how-spains-conservatives-joined-forces-with-far-right-vox&quot;&gt;supported by&lt;/a&gt; the far-right, anti-immigrant Vox party. As a result, PP politicians have lurched further to the right, leading to motions such as the one recently seen in Jumilla, a town of about 27,000 residents, where the PP-led council &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/aug/12/spanish-town-jumilla-ordered-to-scrap-ban-on-muslim-religious-festivals-in-public-spaces&quot;&gt;backed a ban on religious gatherings&lt;/a&gt; in public sports centres that appeared to target Muslims.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;N&uacute;&ntilde;ez P&eacute;rez bristled at the comparison. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve always said that I&rsquo;m not paid by my party, I&rsquo;m paid by the people of this town,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;In my party, as in all parties, there are differences of opinion. But if you look at the wider picture, we&rsquo;re not that different.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was, after all, the PP who had carried out &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.newtral.es/las-regularizaciones-extraordinarias-de-inmigrantes-que-ha-habido-en-espana/20240412/&quot;&gt;more regularisation programmes than any other party&lt;/a&gt; since Spain returned to democracy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Others in the PP had also followed in N&uacute;&ntilde;ez P&eacute;rez&rsquo;s footsteps; in late September, about 20 miles (32km) away in the town of Tarazona de la Mancha, a similar mix of councillors, though headed by a Socialist mayor, had &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.eldiario.es/castilla-la-mancha/provincias/albacete/segundo-caso-albacete-psoe-pp-e-iu-vuelven-ponerse-acuerdo-pedir-regularizacion-migrantes_1_12634292.amp.html&quot;&gt;come together&lt;/a&gt; to unanimously pass their own motion calling on the central government to grant papers to undocumented migrants.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Even so, N&uacute;&ntilde;ez P&eacute;rez knew that the fact that he was a conservative mayor backing regularisation had become a &ldquo;morbid&rdquo; fascination for many. &ldquo;But I think it&rsquo;s the most natural thing; I know what happens in my town, we live quietly, we live in peace and we learn from each other,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;In interviews they always ask me about my political party. But just because someone fires a shot over there, it doesn&rsquo;t mean we&rsquo;re all going to do the same.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;', 'Ashifa Kassam in Villamalea, Albacete', 'articles/68ea5cf9238d2.jpg', 'published', 'Guardian', 1, 25, '2025-10-11 09:09:10', '2025-10-11 10:34:49'),
(26, 'Tony Blair met Jeffrey Epstein in No 10 on advice of Peter Mandelson, documents reveal', 'tony-blair-met-jeffrey-epstein-in-no-10-on-advice-of-peter-mandelson-documents-reveal', 'National Archives papers show how then MP pushed for 2002 meeting between PM and ‘young and vibrant’ financier', '&lt;p&gt;Sir Tony Blair met Jeffrey Epstein in Downing Street while he was prime minister after a recommendation by Peter Mandelson, newly released papers from the National Archives show.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Epstein visited Blair on 14 May 2002, after the suggestion by Lord Mandelson to the prime minister&rsquo;s then chief of staff, Jonathan Powell.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Mandelson was &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2025/sep/11/keir-starmer-sacks-peter-mandelson-over-jeffrey-epstein-revelations&quot;&gt;sacked as US ambassador in September&lt;/a&gt; after new information emerged about how close he was to the convicted sex offender.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At the time of the recommendation, Mandelson was a backbench Labour MP but still served as a trusted ally to Blair. Just over a year earlier he had resigned from government &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/jan/24/labour.labour1997to99&quot;&gt;a second time amid controversy.&lt;/a&gt; He had described Epstein to Powell as &ldquo;safe&rdquo; and a &ldquo;friend&rdquo; in an email before the meeting.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Powell is now Keir Starmer&rsquo;s national security adviser. His role has been questioned in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2025/oct/06/jonathan-powell-to-face-mps-over-role-in-collapse-of-espionage-trial&quot;&gt;collapse of a Chinese spying case.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;aside class=&quot;element element-rich-link element--thumbnail&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;span&gt;Related: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2025/oct/11/tony-blair-and-nick-clegg-hosted-dinner-giving-tech-bosses-access-to-uk-minister&quot;&gt;Tony Blair and Nick Clegg hosted dinner giving tech bosses access to UK minister&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/aside&gt;  &lt;p&gt;According to papers released to the BBC, a briefing memo by the senior civil servant Matthew Rycroft described Epstein as a friend of Mandelson and the then US president Bill Clinton, as well as being close to Prince Andrew, the Duke of York.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A spokesperson for Blair said the meeting was &ldquo;long before his [Epstein&rsquo;s] crimes were known of and his subsequent conviction&rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A government spokesperson said Powell had only forwarded the request in his role as chief of staff. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Epstein pleaded guilty to soliciting prostitution from a minor in June 2008. He died in prison in 2019.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The release of the documents had been blocked by government officials over concerns it may affect UK-US relations. However, the National Archives has now released the document as a result of a freedom of information request.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The BBC &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/c5yk16gpxj0o&quot;&gt;reported that an email from Mandelson to Powell&lt;/a&gt; a week before the meeting said: &ldquo;Do you remember when Clinton saw TB [Tony Blair] he said he wanted to introduce his travelling friend, Jeffrey Epstein, to TB?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;This was frustrated &ndash; TB said at the time &ndash; in the office for reasons (he says) he was unclear about. I think TB would be interested in meeting Jeffrey, who is also a friend of mine, because Jeffrey is an active scientific catalyst/entrepreneur as well as someone who has his finger on the pulse of many worldwide markets and currencies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;He is young and vibrant. He is safe (whatever that means) and Clinton is now doing a lot of travelling with him.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Mandelson went on: &ldquo;I mentioned to TB that Jeffrey is in London next week and he said he would like to meet him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;I have ascertained from Jeffrey that he is flexible &ndash; he could be here any time from Tuesday onwards to fit round the diary &ndash; but would obviously need to know reasonably quickly so as to re-schedule accordingly. Can you let me know?&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A later briefing by Rycroft &ndash; who went on to serve as permanent secretary at the Home Office until 2025 &ndash; on the day of the meeting said about Epstein: &ldquo;He is a financial adviser to the super-rich and a property developer. He is a friend of Bill Clinton and Peter Mandelson.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He added: &ldquo;The background on Epstein is that he is very rich and close to the Duke of York.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He continued: &ldquo;Peter says that Epstein now travels with Clinton and Clinton wants you to meet him.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A spokesperson for Blair said: &ldquo;As far as he can remember, Mr Blair met with him for less than 30 minutes in Downing Street in 2002 and discussed US and UK politics.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;He never met or engaged with him subsequently. This was, of course, long before his crimes were known of and his subsequent conviction.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A government spokesperson said: &ldquo;Jonathan Powell forwarded on the request, he had no further role.&rdquo; &lt;/p&gt;', 'Harry Taylor', 'articles/68ea5cf98fe7b.jpg', 'published', 'Guardian', 1, 30, '2025-10-11 09:09:10', '2025-10-11 10:34:49'),
(27, 'World No 204 Valentin Vacherot topples Djokovic to make history in Shanghai', 'world-no-204-valentin-vacherot-topples-djokovic-to-make-history-in-shanghai', 'Valentin Vacherot became the lowest-ranked Masters 1000 finalist by beating an ailing Novak Djokovic 6-3, 6-4, while Coco Gauff made the Wuhan final', '&lt;p&gt;Valentin Vacherot continued his fairytale run through the Shanghai Masters draw by toppling an injured Novak Djokovic 6-3, 6-4 to become the lowest-ranked Masters 1000 finalist.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In his first match against a top-five opponent, let alone the greatest men&rsquo;s player of all time, the Mon&eacute;gasque world No 204 maintained his composure as he punished a hampered Djokovic, who appeared to struggle with his left gluteal muscle from early in the first set.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;aside class=&quot;element element-rich-link element--thumbnail&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;span&gt;Related: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2025/oct/10/all-fluffed-up-why-modern-balls-are-causing-frustration-and-injury-in-tennis&quot;&gt;All fluffed up: why modern balls are sparking injury worries and frustration in tennis&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/aside&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Having entered the tournament as the second-lowest direct entrant into the qualifying draw, Vacherot has put together one of the most shocking runs at a big tournament, winning eight matches over the past two weeks. That has included victories over the No 14 seed, Alexander Bublik, and Holger Rune, the 10th seed, alongside this giantkilling win over Djokovic, the fourth seed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;This is just crazy,&rdquo; Vacherot said on court. &ldquo;It was an hour and 40 minutes of pure joy, even though not many people wanted me to keep going. He&rsquo;s really appreciated here. I got a bit lost in all his titles when they were announcing him, but it was an unreal experience.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;While Vacherot&rsquo;s career-high ranking currently sits at No 110, the second and third lowest-ranked Masters 1000 semi-finalists, No 191 Andrei Pavel and No 152 Borna Coric, were former top 20 players who had dropped down the rankings. Nothing like this has ever happened at a Masters 1000 event on the ATP tour.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Vacherot&rsquo;s run has been an incredible spectacle by itself, but it has been made even more remarkable by the events in the top half of the draw. His cousin Arthur Rinderknech, the world No 54, has simultaneously put together the best result of his career by reaching the semi-finals. He faces the former ATP No 1 Daniil Medvedev in the second semi-final on Saturday.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The cousins, who played college tennis in the US for the Texas A&amp;amp;M Aggies, have been encouraging each other throughout their breakthrough runs. After closing out the victory, Vacherot signed the broadcast camera lens: &ldquo;Aggies on top! Allez, Arthur!&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Vacherot&rsquo;s joy contrasted sharply with Djokovic&rsquo;s misery as the 38-year-old continued to battle his own body. This had already been a challenging week for the Serb, who had suffered badly in the suffocating heat and humidity during the opening rounds, vomiting several times on court.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It appeared that Djokovic had recovered from those early difficulties well, but it became clear early in set one that he was struggling badly with injury. Djokovic took a medical time out at 3-4 in the first set and, despite the Chinese crowd urging him on, he was clearly unable to move properly until the end of the match.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Facing an injured player can still be challenging, particularly when that opponent is Djokovic, and Vacherot held his nerve in a protracted final game to close out the match. He looked apologetic as he shook Djokovic&rsquo;s hands, but the Serb admirably offered him encouragement during their embrace: &ldquo;You deserve it. You deserve it, man. You played unbelievable,&rdquo; he said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Not only had Djokovic been attempting to become the oldest Masters 1000 champion, he had already become the oldest quarter-finalist at this level. He has shown this year that he is still the third best player in the world behind the untouchable duo of Carlos Alcaraz and Jannik Sinner.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;However, there is a reason why nobody at his age has achieved the milestones he continues to reach. The countless physical problems Djokovic has struggled with between his positive performances this year have further underlined the difficulty of continuing to compete at the highest level after so many years and miles in his legs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In some ways, Djokovic may reflect even more bitterly on this result than some of his grand slam losses this year. While he has been outplayed by Alcaraz and Sinner in the past three major tournaments, things finally &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2025/oct/09/novak-djokovic-holger-rune-valentin-vacherot-zizou-bergs-shanghai-masters-semi-finals&quot;&gt;seemed to line up in his favour&lt;/a&gt; this week after Alcaraz withdrew because of the ankle injury he sustained during his Tokyo title run and then &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2025/oct/05/jannik-sinner-retires-cramp-tallon-griekspoor-shanghai-masters-tallon&quot;&gt;Sinner retired from his third-round match&lt;/a&gt; against Tallon Griekspoor due to the punishing conditions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Djokovic has bluntly recognised that Alcaraz and Sinner are levels above him right now, but if he continues to put himself in good positions, he may give himself a few more opportunities to achieve great things. This week represented one of those opportunities for the 24-time grand slam champion, who has not won a Masters 1000 event since 2023. Instead, his ageing body failed him again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Elsewhere, Coco Gauff beat Italy&rsquo;s Jasmine Paolini 6-4, 6-3 to reach the Wuhan Open final, the French Open champion&rsquo;s third WTA 1000 final of the year, and set up a meeting with Jessica Pegula on Sunday. In Saturday&rsquo;s second semi-final, the American stunned the world No 1, Aryna Sabalenka, by beating the Belarusian 2-6, 6-4, 7-6(2).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This report will update&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;', 'Tumaini Carayol', 'articles/68ea5cfa07cf3.jpg', 'published', 'Guardian', 1, 26, '2025-10-11 09:09:11', '2025-10-11 10:34:50'),
(28, 'Revealed: Labour-run council using legal loophole to serve families with no-fault evictions', 'revealed-labour-run-council-using-legal-loophole-to-serve-families-with-no-fault-evictions', 'Exclusive: London council created an arm’s-length body to manage some of its housing stock', '&lt;p&gt;A Labour-run council is using a legal loophole to issue dozens of families with no-fault evictions, despite Keir Starmer&rsquo;s manifesto pledge to outlaw the practice.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/money/article/2024/sep/06/labour-moves-to-end-no-fault-evictions-within-months&quot;&gt;Scrapping no-fault evictions&lt;/a&gt; &ldquo;immediately&rdquo; was one of Labour&rsquo;s main manifesto pledges before its 2024 election win, but more than a year on, the party&rsquo;s flagship renters&rsquo; rights bill has not been made law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Local authorities cannot normally carry out no-fault evictions &ndash; known officially as section 21 evictions &ndash; as they apply to tenancies issued by private landlords.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;However, Lambeth council in south London has been able to start eviction proceedings against 63 households because it created an arm&rsquo;s-length body to manage some of its housing stock.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Five families have already been issued with possession orders via the courts and two of those have had their homes repossessed by bailiffs. Another 24 have left properties voluntarily after receiving a section 21 notice.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Internal council documents seen by the Guardian suggest that council officials have been planning to regain possession of the properties since at least 2023, but the full implementation of the scheme was delayed until after last year&rsquo;s election.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;An internal briefing document from March 2024 read: &ldquo;Advice received from democratic and legal services [is] that this is a key decision and it is too controversial to take during the pre-election period.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Plans to evict the tenants were made despite the fact Lambeth council wrote to the Conservative government in 2019, asking it to end no-fault evictions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The tenancies were overseen by Homes for Lambeth, a group of companies wholly owned by the council. It was established in 2017 as part of an estate regeneration scheme. As part of this initiative, the local authority bought back some properties from residents who had purchased former council houses at a discount as part of the right-to-buy scheme introduced by Margaret Thatcher&rsquo;s government in 1980.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The council then transferred these properties to Homes for Lambeth. This meant they were able to be rented on the private market, despite ultimately being owned by the local authority. At its peak, Homes for Lambeth managed about 200 properties across six estates.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;However, Homes for Lambeth is now being disbanded due to concerns over poor performance after an independent review by former senior civil servant Bob Kerslake in 2022. Kerslake recommended that management of the Homes for Lambeth stock be brought back &ldquo;in house&rdquo; to improve efficiency.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;About 100 of the homes were vacated voluntarily before eviction notices were issued. The council is now using legal measures in an attempt to regain possession of the remaining properties. In internal documents, it said this would help it meet the &ldquo;most urgent&rdquo; housing needs in the borough, including accommodating vulnerable families who needed temporary housing after being made homeless.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Some residents tried to challenge the decision in court, but in June a judge ruled that current laws do not prevent councils from setting up companies to issue private tenancies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jules Zakolska, 27, who received a section 21 notice in April, has been at the forefront of efforts to fight the decision on behalf of the affected residents. She said some have been driven to the brink of suicide by the stress. Zakolska said she and her partner, July Kaliszewska, 24, had also suffered severe mental health issues as they faced the prospect of their home being repossessed by bailiffs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Zakolska, a university social sciences student, has lived in the property in Clapham with Kaliszewska, a bar manager, for three years. She is autistic and suffers from fibromyalgia, a chronic condition that causes pain and fatigue. She says she is &ldquo;traumatised&rdquo; by the prospect of ending up in temporary accommodation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She said: &ldquo;Lambeth just doesn&rsquo;t care. It says it wants to provide housing for the most vulnerable people, but if it makes us homeless, we will become those people. They have created this issue and traumatised us. It&rsquo;s not right. I&rsquo;m struggling. Who wouldn&rsquo;t be, with the prospect of becoming homeless? It&rsquo;s taken over my life.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A Lambeth council spokesperson said: &ldquo;With almost 5,000 vulnerable homeless Lambeth families staying in often poor-quality temporary accommodation every night, there are incredibly difficult choices to be made. To do nothing would ignore their plight.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;When the opportunity arose we chose, legally, to use properties we own to house the homeless rather than rent them out privately on a short-term basis.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;The majority of these homes have been returned to the council. We have supported tenants who needed help through this process, while successfully giving dozens of homeless families a roof over their heads.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;This situation is just one example of what long-term structural underfunding of council services, the national failure to build the homes we need, and the ongoing housing crisis looks like on the frontline.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;The high cost of housing in Lambeth and across inner city London is a huge driver of deprivation &ndash; a point we are working hard to communicate to government.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A spokesperson for the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government said: &ldquo;We need to do everything we can to support people out of homelessness and we are open to new approaches on this.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;We are spending &pound;1bn on homelessness and building 1.5m homes, so we can tackle the housing crisis we inherited and help councils like Lambeth manage housing need in their areas.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;', 'Geraldine McKelvie', 'articles/68ea48e7c5238.jpg', 'published', 'Guardian', 1, NULL, '2025-10-11 09:09:11', '2025-10-11 09:09:11'),
(29, 'Ross Wilson ends Newcastle sporting director saga in switch from Forest', 'ross-wilson-ends-newcastle-sporting-director-saga-in-switch-from-forest', 'Eddie Howe has linked up with Ross Wilson at Newcastle after a compensation deal was agreed with Forest', '&lt;p&gt;Ross Wilson has filled the vacant sporting director role at Newcastle, drawing to a close one of English football&rsquo;s longest-running pursuits.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Talks about Wilson&rsquo;s departure from Nottingham Forest are completed, with Newcastle finalising an undisclosed compensation deal with Forest. One of Wilson&rsquo;s first tasks in his new role role will be attempting to persuade Sandro Tonali to sign a new contract, extending the Italy midfielder&rsquo;s deal beyond 2028.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;aside class=&quot;element element-rich-link element--thumbnail&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;span&gt;Related: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/oct/10/flag-alert-gary-neville-orwell-english-patriot&quot;&gt;Flag alert! Gary Neville may not be Orwell but he is a very English type of patriot | Barney Ronay&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/aside&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Wilson said on Saturday he was delighted to join Newcastle, adding: &ldquo;This is such a special club. I fully understand the passion, ambition and expectations of our incredible supporters as well as the ambition and desire of our ownership to keeping developing and building an even stronger Newcastle United.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;My conversations with the ownership have been extremely positive and I&rsquo;ve also been in regular contact with both Eddie Howe and David Hopkinson [the new chief executive]. The trust, cohesion and alignment we&rsquo;re building already feels strong.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&ldquo;I&rsquo;m excited to work with everyone across the different areas within our football department from the first team to the women&rsquo;s team and the academy. There&rsquo;s already excellent work being done but my aim is to build on that.&rdquo;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Howe has advocated for Wilson&rsquo;s appointment since &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/jun/02/newcastle-united-paul-mitchell-eddie-howe-pif-saudi-arabia&quot;&gt;Paul Mitchell stood down&lt;/a&gt; as Newcastle&rsquo;s sporting director in June. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Prising Ross &ndash; who was part of the visiting contingent as &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/oct/05/newcastle-nottingham-forest-premier-league-match-report&quot;&gt;Newcastle beat Ange Postecoglou&rsquo;s side&lt;/a&gt; at St James&rsquo; Park last Sunday &ndash; out of the City Ground has proved slow and complicated, particularly as Forest&rsquo;s owner, Evangelos Marinakis was reluctant to lose the highly regarded 41-year-old. Wilson may have feared the prospect of Edu treading on his toes after Marinakis hired Arsenal&rsquo;s former sporting director as Forest&rsquo;s global head of football this summer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;After arriving in the East Midlands from Glasgow, where he had previously shone in an administrative role at Rangers, Wilson played a big part in shaping Forest&rsquo;s recruitment strategy, while supervising upgrades of the club&rsquo;s academy, women&rsquo;s team, medical department and general infrastructure. It did not go unnoticed that Wilson&rsquo;s influence helped persuade key signings, including Elliot Anderson, Anthony Elanga, Nikola Milenkovic and Callum Hudson-Odoi, to join Forest.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Elanga was sold to Newcastle for &pound;55m this summer, the deal representing a healthy profit on a player who cost Forest a relatively modest &pound;13.5m when he joined from Manchester United in July 2023. Newcastle have traditionally been poor sellers and it is hoped Wilson will improve this aspect of their recruitment operation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He will become Newcastle&rsquo;s third sporting director in two years and there is confidence at the club that he will remain in situ for considerably longer than his two immediate predecessors. While Mitchell never really bonded with Howe, Dan Ashworth&rsquo;s head was turned by an offer from Manchester United.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Wilson is expected to be heavily involved with the women&rsquo;s team and plans for a new training ground. The idea is that he will enjoy a collaborative relationship with Howe that involves Newcastle&rsquo;s manager having a final say on all signings and outgoings. Howe&rsquo;s nephew, Andy Howe, is expected to continue to in a senior recruitment role.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Howe&rsquo;s enthusiasm at Wilson&rsquo;s appointment is shared by Newcastle&rsquo;s Saudi Arabian owners and the Canadian Hopkinson.&lt;/p&gt;', 'Louise Taylor', 'articles/68ea48e83a3e0.jpg', 'published', 'Guardian', 1, NULL, '2025-10-11 09:09:12', '2025-10-11 09:09:12');
